particle distribution piles up at the maximum energy given by the
electric potential drop and is focused into a thin fan beam. Applying
this model to the Crab Nebula, we find that the emerging synchrotron
emission spectrum peaks above 100 MeV and is close to the spectral shape
of a single electron. The flare inverse Compton emission is negligible
and no detectable emission is expected at other wavelengths. This
mechanism provides a plausible explanation for the gamma-ray flares in
the Crab Nebula and could be at work in other astrophysical objects such
as relativistic jets in active galactic nuclei.},
